This is the first study on the genetic diversity of tomato exploring genetic resistance and biochemical changes in response to 

A. alternata

infection using ISSR as genetic markers. Our findings support the conclusion that different tomato genotypes have different reactions to 

A. alternata

at transplanting and maturing stages (

, 

; 

). Although there was a significant difference in resistance to EB disease among tomato genotypes at both growth stages, disease severity was more pronounced at the maturing stage. Highly infected genotypes at the maturing stage exhibit more resistance arising from the influence of plant age (

; 

; 

).

In the recent literature, resistance variation to EB disease was known to be mainly associated with genetic variation within the studied genotypes. However, there are limited reports on extensive evaluation for genetic EB disease -resistance in tomato genotypes (

; 

; 

). Characterization of genotypes based on ISSR markers has gained attention for genetic variation analysis (

). In the present study, the UBC855, UBC880 and INC3 primers were identified as more reproducible and polymorphic primers with an average of 6.18 bands; 

also found that UBC855 and UBC880 were highly polymorphic primers.

The highest genetic distance obtained in our results revealed significant genetic differences of susceptible and resistant genotypes (

). Clearly, the major genetic variations (97%) obtained within tested genotypes suggest the effectiveness of ISSR markers in identifying higher genetic diversity within genotype groups rather than between the groups (

).

Pathogenesis-related proteins (PRs) have been found to enhance the defensive capacity of plants in necrotic infection (
;
). We have shown that in tomato, the increased expression of PR proteins, Î²-1,3-glucanase and chitinase, was related to the resistance response to
A. alternata
infection (
). In the present study, the enzyme activity analysis showed increased activity of enzymatic antioxidants, CAT, POD, PAL and SOD, in the inoculated tomato genotypes, suggesting possible contribution to plant defense response. Accumulation of CAT and SOD under disease conditions has been reported to promote plant defense responses (
; w.
). In our study, during infection with
A. alternata ,
the PAL (5-fold at transplanting stage) and POD (3-fold at maturing stage) enzyme activities were markedly increased in the inoculated resistant genotypes compared with the controls and susceptible genotypes. Thus, our findings supported the previous study of
that
A. alternata
infection significantly increased activities of POD and PAL enzymes.

Two seedlings of each genotype were transferred to 5 kg plastic pots filled with a sterilized soil, sand and peat moss (1:1:1) substrate at first fully expanded true leaf stage (
;
). Screening was conducted at transplanting and maturing stages in the greenhouse, and biochemical and genetic assays carried out in the laboratory of the Agricultural and Natural Resources Research and Education center of Esfahan , Iran . The experiments were arranged in a completely randomized design with 3 replications and 10 plants of each genotype per replication.

The pathogen strain ( KY322589 ) was isolated from infected tomato leaves. The isolate was cultured in PDA and incubated for 15 days at 24 Â± 1 â—¦ C, before induction of sporulation as demonstrated by
under cool-white fluorescent light with a 12-h photoperiod (
). Genotypes were screened for EB resistance. Inocula preparation was carried as described by
. The conidial suspension (10 5 sporesâˆ™mL 1 ) was sprayed 3 times in a 3-day interval at transplanting and mature stages, on the foliage, under 27 Â± 1 â—¦ C, 16-h photoperiod, and 65% relative humidity. Screening assays were performed at transplanting (6-week) and maturing (12-week) after transplanting. At 20 days after inoculation at both stages after emergence of symptoms, disease progress was evaluated. Disease severity was assessed based on infection percent (0â€“100) against the scoring scales of: 0, 5, 10, 25, 50, 75 or 100% (
;
, 2019). Controls consisted of plants in pots without inoculation.

To estimate defense-related enzymes, 14 susceptible and resistant genotypes of tomato were selected based on screening (
Table 1
). After re-inoculation at transplanting and mature stages, third leaves of the tomato genotypes from control, non-inoculated genotypes and inoculated groups were collected separately as samples and stored in aluminum foil at 80 
â—¦
C for enzyme extraction. All experiments were repeated 3 times (

).

The EB disease severity data were converted using Asin âˆšx + 0.5 for homogeneity, and analysis of variance was performed using SAS (ver. 9.4, SAS Institute, Cary, NC) (SAS, 2004), and the means were compared using least significant difference (LSD). Statistical analysis was done by GenStat software (GenStat for Windows, 6th VSN International, 
UK
). Analysis of variance (ANOVA) was performed to evaluate the impact of different genotypes on EB disease severity. Pearson correlation analysis was also carried out to analyze the relationship among the tomato genotypes and response variability and cluster analysis of data was performed using SPSS software (

; 

).

The PCR products were scored as present = 1 or absent = 0. Polymorphism levels and calculated by separating polymorphic bands from total scored bands. The Similarity for Qualitative Data (SIMQUAL) routine was used to determine the Jacquard similarity coefficient. A dendrogram with the Unweighted Pair Group Method with Arithmetic Average (UPGMA) algorithm was constructed using NTSYS software (ver. 2.1, Numerical taxonomy and multivariate analysis system, Applied Biostatistics, 
New York
, 
USA
). The distribution of genetic variation within, and among, groups, was detected using the molecular variance analysis (AMOVA) in GenAlEx software (

). Genetic variation indices, including effective numbers of alleles (Ne), Shannonâ€™ s information index (
I
), Neiâ€™ s gene diversity (
H
), percent of polymorphic loci (PPL), were estimated using POP-GENE software (

). All data were in triplicate.
